Plotting the chart for Top10 Youtubers in terms of Subscribers¶

In [184]:
# Sort by subscribers and select top 10
top_10 = df.sort_values('subscribers', ascending=False).head(10)

# Create a color palette
colors = plt.cm.viridis(np.linspace(0, 1, 10))

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
bars = plt.bar(top_10['Youtuber'], top_10['subscribers'], color=colors)

# Add labels and title
plt.ylabel('Subscribers')
plt.xlabel('Youtubers')
plt.title('Top 10 YouTubers by Subscribers')

# Add a label on top of each bar indicating the number of subscribers
for bar in bars:
    yval = bar.get_height()
    yval_millions = yval / 1_000_000  # Convert to millions
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval + 0.05*yval, f'{yval_millions:.2f}M', ha='center', va='bottom')

# Rotate x-axis labels if they overlap
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

How does video views correlate with the number of subscribers?¶

In [72]:
# Define the data for the scatter plot
x = df['subscribers']
y = df['video views']

# Plot a scatter plot of the 'subscribers' column versus the 'video views' column
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.scatter(x, y, color='skyblue')

# Calculate the line of best fit
coefficients = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
polynomial = np.poly1d(coefficients)
ys = polynomial(x)

# Plot the line of best fit
plt.plot(x, ys, color='red')

plt.title('Correlation Between Subscribers and Video Views')
plt.xlabel('Number of Subscribers')
plt.ylabel('Number of Video Views')
plt.show()

# Calculate and print the correlation coefficient
corr_coef = np.corrcoef(x, y)[0,1]
print(f'Correlation Coefficient: {corr_coef:.2f}')

Correlation Coefficient: 0.74

As the graph suggests, Video Views and Subcribers are highly correlated. And Channels with more subscribers do have more views.¶
